questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: Sentinel surveillance is when an institution provides health data.
questions.explanation: True. Sentinel surveillance relies on data from a network of selected reporting sites (sentinels) to monitor disease trends.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: These are (in general) the correct steps involved in the investigation of an outbreak.
questions.explanation: False. The image likely shows an incorrect or incomplete sequence. A standard outbreak investigation follows a systematic process, including confirming the outbreak, establishing a case definition, and implementing control measures.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: One apparent reason for an increased infection rate during an outbreak can be the idea that there is an increase in testing.
questions.explanation: True. Increased testing can lead to the identification of more cases, including those that might have otherwise gone undetected, which can contribute to a perceived rise in infection rates.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: A case definition includes: time, place, person, clinical and lab.
questions.explanation: True. A comprehensive case definition uses these five criteria (person, place, time, clinical features, and laboratory results) to accurately identify cases during an outbreak investigation.

questions.subject: Microbiology
questions.question: After control measures are implemented, active surveillance is important to ensure these measures are working.
questions.explanation: True. Active surveillance is essential for monitoring the effectiveness of control measures and detecting any new cases to ensure the outbreak is contained.
